TY  - CONF
TI  - Research on Operational State Prediction and Optimization Methods for New Energy Equipment Based on Digital Twins
AU  - Y. Wu
T2  - 2025 4th International Conference on Clean Energy Storage and Power Engineering (CESPE)
AB  - To address the complex operational characteristics, fluctuating efficiency, and insufficient predictive capability of new energy equipment, this study proposes a digital twin-based operational state prediction and optimization framework. The approach establishes a high-fidelity virtual-physical mapping system integrating real-time sensor data, process models, and historical operational records. A hybrid prediction model combining Temporal Convolutional Networks (TCN) and gated recurrent units (GRU) is constructed to capture nonlinear temporal dependencies and improve fault trend prediction accuracy. The optimization layer introduces a multi-objective strategy based on Pareto dominance, balancing energy consumption, system stability, and prediction precision. The system architecture encompasses data acquisition, model training, and optimization control, achieving closed-loop synchronization between the physical and virtual environments. Experimental validation on a wind–solar hybrid energy platform demonstrates that the proposed model improves prediction accuracy by $9.4 \%$, enhances energy optimization efficiency by $12.7 \%$, and reduces latency by $31 \%$ compared with conventional methods. The results confirm that digital twin-driven state prediction provides effective support for intelligent operation and maintenance, enabling adaptive scheduling and real-time fault prevention in new energy systems. This research offers practical guidance for constructing intelligent, efficient, and sustainable energy management frameworks in future industrial application.
