TI  - Blockchain Technologies for Traceability and Efficiency in Service-Sector Supply Chains
AU  - J. Curado
AU  - A. L. Martins
AU  - J. C. Ferreira
T2  - 2025 IEEE International Conference on Distributed Ledger Technologies (ICDLT)
AB  - Liquids-focused service-sector supply chains (healthcare cold chain, maritime documentation, luxury spirits) face concurrent challenges in traceability, privacy, and throughput. We present a modular blockchain architecture that combines a permissioned core with zeroknowledge proofs (zk-SNARKs) for selective disclosure, Layer-2 batching for scale, and IoT edge ingestion for realtime monitoring. Using Design Science Research, we design, prototype, and simulate representative workloads. Under WAN latencies typical of port operations, L2 batching reduces end-to-end verification latency relative to a Fabriconly baseline; in cold-chain scenarios, proof cadence tuning maintains privacy with bounded overhead. We discuss oracle and interoperability risks and provide a cost model. Results and artifacts are intended to guide practitioners balancing privacy, performance, and compliance in regulated logistics.
