TI  - Research on Cloud Edge Collaborative Algorithm for Electricity Safety Inspection Based on Multidimensional Cost Planning
AU  - Y. Liang
AU  - B. Wang
AU  - O. Wang
AU  - Q. Zhao
AU  - H. Liu
AU  - R. Lin
T2  - 2025 8th International Conference on Intelligent Robotics and Control Engineering (IRCE)
AB  - This article explores how cloud-edge collaborative algorithm allocation can significantly enhance the efficiency and decision-making quality of electricity safety inspectors amidst the increasing complexities of modern power grids. As the demand for electricity escalates, along with a rising share of renewable energy and the frequent occurrence of natural disasters, conventional monitoring and inspection methods are becoming insufficient. These methods struggle to keep pace with the growing complexities and expanded scale of power networks. This has driven the adoption of cutting-edge technologies such as the Internet of Things (IoT), edge computing, 5 G communications, and artificial intelligence. These technologies aim to elevate system performance and foster automation and smart management across power systems. In response to these challenges, this study introduces a specialized cloud-edge collaborative computing framework designed specifically for electricity safety inspections. This framework is complemented by sophisticated task allocation algorithms that are crafted to optimize resource utilization. The algorithms consider several critical factors, such as the real-time requirements of system operations, the load on individual network nodes, prevailing network conditions, and the necessities of service migration. Such considerations ensure that the deployment of resources is both strategic and efficient, enhancing overall system responsiveness and reliability. Furthermore, by refining the electricity safety inspection processes and integrating edge computing technology, the research seeks to pioneer a more effective and intelligent model for power system safety management. The framework detailed in this paper delineates the structure of the inspection system, illustrating the distinct roles played by the cloud layer, the edge layer, and the terminal layer. Additionally, it elaborates on the advanced algorithms employed for task allocation and decision-making. These algorithms are pivotal in managing the complex data and operational demands of modern electric grids, thereby supporting more informed decision making and enhancing the preventive safety measures crucial for maintaining grid integrity.
