TY  - JOUR
TI  - Real-Time Monitoring Method for Underground Laying Quality of Ultrahigh Voltage Cables Based on Distributed Measurement Networks and Digital Twins
AU  - C. Wang
AU  - Z. Hu
AU  - L. Tao
T2  - IEEE Transactions on Instrumentation and Measurement
AB  - With the widespread application of ultrahigh voltage (UHV) cables in urban power transmission, ensuring quality control and safety during underground installation presents significant challenges. To address potential hazards such as excessive bending radius, local overpressure, and speed fluctu ations, this article proposes a real-time monitoring method for underground UHV cable laying. The method integrates a distributed measurement network (including vertical side pressure sensors, multidimensional side pressure sensors, and speed and meter sensors) with digital twins to enable comprehensive state monitoring and dynamic optimization of the cable-laying process. By employing a Unity3D–COMSOL coupled simulation engine, the approach establishes a risk prediction mechanism driven by the curvature–load ratio and velocity–pressure coupling factor, enabling early diagnosis of bending deformation and dynamic load impacts. Experimental results show that the method achieves millisecond-level data synchronization through a Modbus remote terminal unit (RTU)/transmission control protocol (TCP) hybrid protocol. Furthermore, by combining tri-state hierarchical warnings with multiphysical field verification, it effectively identifies risks of mechanical overload and hidden electromagnetic losses. Overall, the research provides intelligent technical support for quality control in complex cable-laying environments and demonstrates strong practical application value.
