TY  - JOUR
TI  - An Enhanced Digital Twin-Driven Fault Diagnosis Approach Based on Deep Multimodal Information Fusion for Marine Machinery
AU  - J. Sun
AU  - H. Ren
AU  - Y. Dong
AU  - B. Zhang
AU  - S. Qiu
AU  - Y. Zhou
T2  - IEEE Sensors Journal
AB  - Condition monitoring and fault diagnosis of marine machinery are essential for ensuring the safety and stability of offshore operations. Traditional approaches, which typically rely solely on either physical mechanisms or large volumes of data, often struggle to achieve both high accuracy and adaptability to component degradation. To address this issue, this article proposes a novel digital twin framework based on deep multimodal information fusion (DMIF-DT) that integrates the complementary strengths of a physics-based model (PBM) and a data-driven model (DDM). An attention-enhanced multiscale convolutional network is developed to extract features from sensor measurements and calibrated simulation data. A low-rank fusion strategy is then employed to map the two modalities into a unified high-dimensional space for effective integration between the PBM and the DDM. Furthermore, a performance-degradation adaptive correction module, based on sensor measurements and probabilistic distribution features, is used to map health factors and feed them back to the PBM for componentlevel correction, thereby supporting periodic model updates. Experimental results show that the proposed DMIF-DT framework significantly reduces parameter prediction errors and achieves an average fault diagnosis accuracy of 98.02% under diverse operating conditions. By uniquely integrating a performance-degradation adaptive correction module with attention-enhanced multimodal fusion, the framework bridges physics-based and data-driven insights, providing a new approach for the intelligent health management of marine machinery.
