TY  - CONF
TI  - Satellite-AIS Fusion for Container Terminal Analytics: Towards Digital Port Operations in Tokyo's Ohi Terminals
AU  - W. Zhang
AU  - R. Shibasaki
T2  - 2025 IEEE International Conference on Big Data (BigData)
AB  - In the era of port digitalization, obtaining real-time, transparent, and comprehensive analytics of container terminal operations is crucial for enhancing efficiency and sustainability. Traditional performance metrics often depend on proprietary, non-public data, which restricts objective analysis and comparability across terminals. This paper proposes a novel spatiotemporal coupling framework that integrates high-resolution satellite imagery with Automatic Identification System (AIS) data to address these challenges. Using Tokyo's Ohi Container Terminals as a case study, we integrate the temporal dynamics of vessel movements from AIS data with the spatial state of the terminal, including yard use and berth occupancy, derived from satellite images processed with a UNetFormer deep learning model. This integration facilitates a new class of analytics, uncovering intricate relationships between vessel traffic patterns and yard congestion cycles. Contrary to the assumption that total yard capacity drives delays, our findings identify physical congestion at the road-yard interface as the primary bottleneck for vessel turnaround efficiency ($\rho=0.96$). Furthermore, longitudinal analysis reveals structural resilience within the terminal ecosystem, where functional specialization enables the port to maintain throughput efficiency by balancing high-frequency feeder operations with heavy-load handling, even during postpandemic traffic surges. This work presents a replicable, datadriven methodology for third-party port monitoring, facilitating enhanced transparency and efficiency in the global logistics chain.
