TI  - Low-Cost Mini Automated Guided Vehicle (AGV) with AI-Powered Multicolor Line Tracking and Slot Detection for Industrial Automation
AU  - P. E
AU  - D. Prabhukumar
AU  - S. Revathy
AU  - S. Abishek
AU  - A. S. Kavin
T2  - 2025 2nd International Conference on Artificial Intelligence and Knowledge Discovery in Concurrent Engineering (ICECONF)
AB  - Automated guided vehicles (AGVs) are an essential part of the modern industrial automation process and help move in autonomously navigated material transportation. Nevertheless, commercial AGV systems are too expensive and not very flexible, even when considering small and middle-sized enterprises. This research paper designs a cost-effective, mini miniaturized AGV with artificial intelligence (AI)-based multicolor line tracking and real-time slot detection to fill the affordability-performance gap. The robot uses an ESP32 microcontroller, L298N motor driver, ultrasonic and IR sensors and OV7670 vision modules installed on a lightweight 3D-printed chassis. The bottom point camera reads the multicolored routes with the OpenCV program using the HSV segmentation, which makes it applicable to adjust to various industrial paths. The optimal values of slot occupancy are computed as the prediction output of a lightweight model YOLOv5 processed through TensorRT, providing the average success detection of 94.9% and F1-scores of 95.0. Line tracking precision was 1.49 cm-average deviation across paths of many colors, and obstacle avoidance was 100% hit-rate at less than 2.3% distance estimation error. Inference speed with quantized weights was decreased to the ~75ms range, allowing FPS of 13+ on Raspberry Pi hardware. Power tests run time of more than 2.4 hours under full load. The proposed AGV architecture shows high accuracy, speed of inference, and adaptability in different environments at a low cost design footprint. This allows providing a simple, scalable approach to decentralized automation, typically in small factories, educational labs and warehouses. Future research will focus on collaboration between swarms of vehicles, dynamic path-re-routing, and integration with IIoT -based fleet orchestration and predictive maintenance analytics.
